oo broad for this site, which is why I voted to close this question. Nothing you said is incorrect, but I think it&#39;s a bit misleading. Otherwise, every drug company on earth would be targeting NLRC5 and we&#39;d have cured cancer by now. I know your own research can seem like the most important topic on Earth, but you need to have some broader perspective and a more nuanced view of how cancer works."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bc157317b36b1a885cdac4f53328b426?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20501,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20501/sere","reputation":143,"display_name":"SeRe"},"score":0,"post_id":41331,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449657286,"comment_id":70153,"body":"I never said, that NLRC5 is the only responsible protein for these escape mechanisms. I know, that this topic is much greater, but I don&#180;t know every aspect of it, so I wanted to show at least one aspect. If we want to discuss this question in total, we would have to write a book. So NLRC5 and MHC I are two proteins, which show some insights into this broad field and now 201044 has some indications for research also on other involved molecules, if he is interested."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/40ae400cb04bc03eb9d6573bf4c1d804?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11605,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11605/201044","reputation":279,"display_name":"201044","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":41331,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450590515,"comment_id":70781,"body":"Great information ; I&#39;m just an amateur researcher or like an &#39;armchair philosopher&#39; I&#39;m an armchair theoretical biologist.  I just wonder if these &#39;escape mechanisms&#39; as mentioned can be inherited by any daughter cells of a pre-cancerous cell?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/40ae400cb04bc03eb9d6573bf4c1d804?s=128&d=identicon&r=