tors of humans underwent a period when they were adapting to an aquatic or semiaquatic way of life, but returned to terrestrial life before having become fully adapted to the aquatic environment.  Is there any new evidence of this?<\/p>\n","question_id":2776,"tags":["evolution"],"score":9,"down_vote_count":2,"is_answered":true,"view_count":508,"up_vote_count":11,"last_edit_date":1452440830},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/15ff0844c660b14c14c76fd1346f61bb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21091,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21091/bean","reputation":38,"display_name":"bean"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42192/about-electrons-returning-to-photosystem-i-when-supply-of-nadp-runs-out-in-photo","last_activity_date":1452435091,"creation_date":1452414606,"answer_count":0,"title":"About electrons returning to photosystem I when supply of NADP runs out in photosynthesis","body":"<p>According to my textbook, in photosynthesis, when the supply of NADP runs out, electrons from photosystem I return to the electron transport chain that links the 2 photosystems and flow back to photosystem I, causing pumping of protons. I don't understand if the electron transport chain that the electrons flow back to is the same one that electrons from photosystem II flow across. Do the electrons pass through ferredoxin again and pass through another electron transport chain to go to photosystem I or do they go through some path to the start of chain of electron carriers following photosystem II, but if they go by this way, do they go back to photosystem I through plastocyanin? How many electron transport chains are in a thylakoid?<\/p>\n","question_id":42192,"tags":["biochemistry","photosynthesis"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":22,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1452435091},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f524f51edb2e0e559de5f027217b2d47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14815,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14815/ro-siv","reputation":535,"display_name":"Ro Siv","accept_rate":97},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":42176,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452395212,"comment_id":72224,"body":"One thing I would point out in your question is that a female identifying as trans-male who has not undergone hormone replacement or reassignment can become pregnant, assuming there are no medical conditions that would prevent a pregnancy. It is only after they are trans-male that they would be incapable of becoming pregnant, unless of course their internal sexual organs were preserved. I think the bigger issue would be that as the person does not identify as female, they would probably not desire to become pregnant, either before or after reassignment."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":42176,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452409256,"comment_id":72236,"body":"Possible duplicate of <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/35128/can-androgen-insensitive-genetic-males-get-pregnant\">Can androgen-insensitive genetic-males get pregnant?<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":42176,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com