lly. The extent and rate of loss is correlated with the number of organelle the cell harbours. The <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/38954/evolution-of-endosymbionts/38956#38956\">limited transfer window hypothesis<\/a> speculates a probable mechanism.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42191,"question_id":42167,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42167/why-only-mitochondria-and-plastids","last_activity_date":1452413378,"creation_date":1452365734,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why only mitochondria and plastids?","body":"<p>Why are there only two unique semi-independent organelles? Why are there no others, symbiogenesis seems like it should be a relatively common thing. So do most organelles just lose all their DNA? Or is it something that occurs fairly rarely?<\/p>\n","question_id":42167,"tags":["cell-biology","symbiosis"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":42191,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":47,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/147f8c2e21fa001311657552faafb9e1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":21085,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21085/user21085","reputation":26,"display_name":"user21085"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9d93c0899fe05ce22895a7e483b9157b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18914,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18914/tusky","reputation":164,"display_name":"Tusky"},"score":0,"post_id":42170,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452408572,"comment_id":72233,"body":"Do you want to know why scars don&#39;t go away? If not please do tell me what you want to know. I&#39;m a bit lost here"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3363534a62c163bf91814cd024889dd8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19568,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19568/joel","reputation":118,"display_name":"Joel"},"sco