"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452494674,"comment_id":72365,"body":"@YviDe: and e.g. one of my master students is working on a multi-agent simulation of the stock market at the moment. This model is able to reproduce many important stylized facts of markets. And, believe me, markets are also very, very complicated beasts. People could tell you that you had to simulate millions of brains that are involved in the process - but that of course misses the point. All models are wrong, some are useful: We have not yet found the right abstract model (from an algorithmics point of view) of <i>real<\/i> evolution that does just the simplifications at the right places."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":1,"post_id":42162,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452500384,"comment_id":72368,"body":"@vonjd If you want to ask about a right model to simulate the evolutionary process then your question should have these: 1. <b>Kind of outcomes do you expect<\/b> (i.e what exactly you are looking for) 2. <b>The scale of the model<\/b> 3. <b>Assumptions you can allow<\/b> 4. <b>Kind of model (deterministic or stochastic)<\/b> 5. <b>Computational resource available<\/b> (optional). You should explain what you have thought of and then ask. You should also go through the existing algorithms. If you are unaware of those then your question should be a reference request asking for papers on evolutionary simulations."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"score":0,"post_id":42162,"edit