or a mutation that causes the gene to be non-functional would be deleterious and could lead to the organisms extinction. A mutation that makes the gene non-functional can occur if there is a symbiont producing the gene product and so you remove selection for that gene and it can mutate to non-function without hurting the host organism."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41926,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451664191,"comment_id":71396,"body":"Substitute cellulase for any trait and that is your question which is why it is a duplicate of that question."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":41926,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451664433,"comment_id":71397,"body":"Why substitute? (don&#39;t mind) This question is specifically about a single trait which, according to me, has probably evolved but never showed up. Anyways, this discussion is now going off-topic, so thanks everyone for your help."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41926,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451664476,"comment_id":71398,"body":"Histidine is one of the most important amino acids for proteins, but humans cannot produce it. So if I asked, Why did humans not evolve (or retain) the gene to produce histidine? then it is a duplicate of that question. That is why we have it as a community wiki."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"re