cose in out guts were fermented into alcohol (this condition does <strong>rarely<\/strong> occur in humans, and the living people afflicted with this are truly afflicted), because we have a gut microbiome, we would walk around drunk much of the time (ok, maybe even only some of the time), which would make escaping predators less drunk than we were difficult. Maybe the body would be incapable of handling that level of glucose ingestion, and we'd all be T2 diabetics by the time we were just out of toddlerhood.<\/p>\n\n<p>Humans need fiber in our GI tracts. I don't know all the reasons why we developed that way, but we do. Cellulase would do away with that. Do you know for sure that this would be good for us?<\/p>\n\n<p>The thing is, you've made an assumption (we'd all be better off with cellulase) that has no evidence to support it <em>at all<\/em> (or, at least you have not provided any.)<\/p>\n\n<p>It's always tricky to assume that you know what's more beneficial for a mammal in the presence of billions of mammals that seem to be doing OK. There are millions of reasons that they <em>are<\/em> doing OK. We don't know all of them, but the <em>absence<\/em> of the very thing you presume would be a benefit may be what allowed vertebrates to develop at all.<\/p>\n\n<p><sub><a href=\"http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/22/5/1273.short\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ancient Origin of Glycosyl Hydrolase Family 9 Cellulase Genes<\/a><\/sub><br>\n<sub><a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378111904004445\" rel=\"nofollow\">Structure and function of a cellulase gene in redclaw crayfish, Cherax quadricarinatus<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":41931,"question_id":41926,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1452298569}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41926/why-is-cellulase-not-found-in-animals","last_activity_date":1452298569,"creation_date":1451653502,"answer_count":1,"title":"why is cellulase not found in animals?","body":"<p>As it is really beneficial for all organisms, why are animals, especially mammals (I don't know about other vertebrates) unable to synthesize cellulase enzyme in their body? Is it linked to some DNA defects or have we not evolved from cellulase producing bacteria?<\/p>\n","question_id":41926,"tags":["dna","digestion"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":41931,"down_vote_count":2,"closed_reason":"primarily opinion-based","is_answered":true,"view_count":105,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1451705836},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11d51f8d530d75176067cf803e3c3d98?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21046,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21046/koffeehaus","reputation":173,"display_name":"Koffeehaus"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":1,"post_id":42124,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452302680,"comment_id":72119,"body":"I voted both answers up, though I think &quot;functional extinction&quot; is the best answer. Theoretically, an animal could be so reduced in numbers that it&#39;s effectively ecologically extinct, even though it&#39;s still able to continue reproducing. Nevertheless, I love the term ecological extinction, partly because it helps make the point that species aren&#39;t just isolated genetic expressions that come and go. Each species has a role to play, and it may stop playing that role long before it becomes extinct."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SGxqm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18860,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18860/harry-vervet","reputation":1769,"display_name":"Harry Vervet"},"score":15,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar