germinate-first","last_activity_date":1452190890,"creation_date":1452095403,"answer_count":1,"title":"Determine which seed will germinate first","body":"<p>I recently studied about plant physiology for a test. Strangely, there was this question which I had no idea how to approach. <\/p>\n\n<p>The question is, \nWhich seed will germinate first?<\/p>\n\n<p>a) Castor<br>\nb) Wheat<br>\nc) Mung( Vigna radiata )<\/p>\n\n<p>The answer is (c). I want to know how do we determine if which seed will germinate first? Which factors does it depend upon?<\/p>\n","question_id":42066,"tags":["botany","homework","plant-physiology","seeds","germination"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":42103,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":51,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1452190890},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49d0d23657ec45eeb254f56f2a0ff6a3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":86,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/86/masi","reputation":2608,"display_name":"Masi","accept_rate":77},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42101/quality-assurance-of-mammography-and-false-negatives-by-kvp","last_activity_date":1452188200,"creation_date":1452184375,"answer_count":0,"title":"Quality assurance of mammography and false negatives by kVp?","body":"<p>Mammography is RTG imaging with customized constraints. False positives are most commonly associated with the imaging. However, there are sometimes false negatives where you cannot see the concentration of lipid/cancer units, while you can in US. \nAssume no hormone replacement therapy (HRT), no history of breast surgery, and standardized body mass index. <\/p>\n\n<p>There is something about the imaging technique and its characteristics with some masses. Those masses have equal RTG characterization when summed up signals from fat, breast glands, breast ducts and cancerous masses. It would be great to understand when the RTG area has equal value. Which are the sufficient parameters and constraints that make enough sensitive RTG area?<\/p>\n\n<h2>Exclusions<\/h2>\n\n<p>Other factors<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>No clinical examination before the imaging; too low dose of the radiation (O\u2019Leary \u2013 Rainford 2012). I think this one is most common reason why you get false negatives because suspicion of breast cancer has a different setting than a normal screening in the imaging. <\/li>\n<li>Too low radiation and hypothesis: no detectable Comptom scattering so no all-directional scattering. <\/li>\n<li>Exclude nursing mistakes about digital-analog, ...  <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<h2>Problem setting<\/h2>\n\n<p>Only one kVp used in determining the quality of the image. <\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>minimize radiation by mAs (milli ampere seconds, intensity of x-ray beam i.e. image density; decreasing it darkens) and <strong>kVp<\/strong> (kilo volt peak) for penetrability so its decrease makes more gray image<\/li>\n<li>maximize sensitivity of the imaging<\/li>\n<li>which constraints?\n\n<ul>\n<li>range of radiation: 30 petahertz to 30 exahertz. How is the radiation region selected? Energy involved 15 to 30 keV. [1]<\/li>\n<li>no coherent scattering i.e. no Rayleigh scattering because breast tissue is gently pressured in the procedure so no fog. [2]<\/li>\n<\/ul><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<h2>[conjuncture] Problem setting by two kVp and a convex problem<\/h2>\n\n<p>Use two kVp's which total radiation exposure is smaller than (1): <\/p>\n\n<p>\\begin{equation}\nx \\cdot kVp_{1} + (1-x) \\cdot kVp_{2} &lt; kVp. \n\\end{equation}<\/p>\n\n<p>Combine the two images, reducing the fog. \nI think this way can contribute better quality of mammography imaging. <\/p>\n\n<h2>Radiation exposure control and quality assurance by kVp<\/h2>\n\n<p>Increasing kVp 15% doubles radiation exposure. [3] So kVp squared to the radiation exposure relationship:<\/p>\n\n<p>\\begin{equation}\n(kVp) \\propto (Ex)^{2}\n\\end{equation}<\/p>\n\n<p>Which are the energy settings used in the RTG? Determined apparently mainly by kVp which misses relevant bands at least with low energy radiation. Most probably as continuous energy spectrum because only the peak is determined. The current RTG settings should include regions of the greatest sensitivity but I did not find any prioritizing by specific regions, only the kVp. I need studies about the sensitivity of kVp in the quality assurance of the mammography. <\/p>\n\n<h2>Sources<\/h2>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Jerrold T. Bushberg, The Essential Physics of Medical Imaging, 2011. <\/li>\n<li>Workbook for Radiation Protection in Medical Radiography. Mary Alice Statkiewicz Sherer, Paula J. <\/li>\n<li>X-Ray mAs vs. kVp, <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uZGPWfOiuvM\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uZGPWfOiuvM<\/a>, visited 7.1.2016.<\/li>\n<li>DynaMed Plus, Mammography. Visited 7.1.2016.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Why is mammography giving false negatives sometimes?<\/p>\n","question_id":42101,"tags":["imaging","mammography"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":10,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1452188200},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/75a9f1f40c68c65a319dac2bdf0aeb5b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21029,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21029/vruvre","reputation":1,"display_name":"vruvre"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42102/indentation-between-trapezius-and-scapula","last_activity_date":1452185332,"creation_date":1452185332,"answer_count":0,"title":"Indentation between trapezius and scapula","body":"<p>I've been studying the muscles of the back, and while browsing through reference pictures on google I've come across this image (coloured lines edited in by me):\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/T0iEZ.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/T0iEZ.png\" alt=\"Marked Example of Indentation between Scapula and Trapezius\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>What I'm confused 