ology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":31854,"edited":false,"creation_date":1430326321,"comment_id":53697,"body":"Too much calcium in the blood seems to be toxic in my experience. I was doing <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16724360\" rel=\"nofollow\">hydrodynamic dosing<\/a>, and my advisor asked me to change the NaCl to CaCl2. Anyway, all the mice that got calcium died quickly, with spasms and what seemed like a faster onset of rigor mortis. We immediately abandoned that project, so I never looked up what exactly causes the toxicity."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1430309675,"creation_date":1430309675,"body":"<p>Because hypercalcemia means <strong>more calcium in the blood, not in the muscle fibers nor in neurons<\/strong>. Calcium transport through the neural and muscle fiber membranes is regulated, so a higher concentration in the plasma tells nothing about intracellular concentration.<\/p>\n\n<p>Secondly, muscle spasms mean muscle contraction, which means action potential. For an action potential to occur, the membrane potential must be high, which means that the intracellular medium must have a higher net charge compared to the extracellular medium. In case of hypercalcemia, the extracellular net charge will increase, <em>i.e<\/em> <strong>an action potential becomes less likely<\/strong>, not more!<\/p>\n","answer_id":31854,"question_id":31735,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ec0HW.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15566,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15566/sarin","reputation":171,"display_name":"Sarin"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8a592159aa380c054cccb3a449a9ff27?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8105,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8105/rover-eye","reputation":2003,"