e Fc part of the primary antibody (which has a species specific sequence) and even with the differences in the sub-classes due to different assembly of the light and heavy chains this will not be detected by the secondaries. See the figure (from <a href=\"http://www4.ac-nancy-metz.fr/svt/enseign/svt/ressourc/rescien/Immuno/immmolec.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>) about the schematic differences:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/22k7t.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/22k7t.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>With a careful selection of the peptides used for immunisation it is possible to generate secondary antibodies which can be used to distinguish between sub-classes.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42060,"question_id":42056,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1452151473}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42056/how-to-choose-secondary-antibody","last_activity_date":1452151473,"creation_date":1452086233,"answer_count":1,"title":"How to choose secondary Antibody?","body":"<p>when isotype of the Primary antibody is IgG2a (from Mouse) and IgG2b (from Rat), how to choose secondary Antibody against these Primary isotypes?\nDoes secondary Antibody is that much specific to detect IgG2a/2b? What is the logic behind choosing secondary antibodies? A detailed note in this regard will highly be appreciated.<\/p>\n","question_id":42056,"tags":["immunology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":29,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SIeaP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3198/bram-vanroy","reputation":143,"display_name":"Bram Vanroy","accept_rate":75},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f59bbb90d826f21c58f4f33c7d61e552?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19614,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19614/donjulian"