t example of spandrel that has been suggested by Gould was the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spotted_hyena#Female_genitalia\" rel=\"nofollow\">genitalia of hyenas<\/a>. At the time the term was created, behavioural consequences of having a big brain was a common example and of course, this does not concern only humans but many other animals.<\/p>\n\n<p>The riddles on the knuckles is another example (that is not specific to humans only either). Those riddles are a by-product of the need the make movement with your fingers. <\/p>\n\n<p>I am personally not a big fan of the term <code>spandrel<\/code> as used in evolutionary biology. This term easily leads to limit cases and it depends on how you define the phenotypic traits and the functions they serve. <\/p>\n","answer_id":31467,"question_id":31457,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1452124889},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/x3tGY.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21002,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21002/biologyofreligion","reputation":1,"display_name":"biologyofreligion"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452121967,"creation_date":1452121967,"body":"<p>While some academics contrive spandrels or non-adaptive byproducts to account for human art and religion, actual empirical support in the scientific literature for non-adaptive byproducts, behavioral or otherwise, is virtually non-existent. The few papers that tackle this question tend to criticize the concept. In <em>Adaptations, Exaptations, and Spandrels,<\/em> lead author David Buss (1998) says, \"Hypotheses about functionless by-products must meet rigorous scientific standards.\" (p. 542) He concludes, \"We could not find a single example of an empirical discovery made about humans as a result of using the concepts of exaptations or spandrels.\" (p. 545) <\/p>\n\n<p>Several proposed examples of possible phenotypic non-adaptive byproducts are male nipples, the navel, and the female hyena's gentalia, which is very male-like. However, there is no analysis in the peer-reviewed literature that meets the scientific criteria for these to be accepted as legitimate non-adaptive byproducts, and there are good reasons why they are not non-adaptive byproducts. The non-adaptive byproduct or spandrel is much like the way in which religion solves the mysteries of life: it is inappropriately utilized to construct answers in the absence of better explanations.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42081,"question_id":31457,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31457/a-non-human-adaptive-behaviour-with-a-spandrel","last_activity_date":1452124889,"creation_date":1429314529,"answer_count":2,"title":"A non human adaptive behaviour with a spandrel","body":"<p>Is there any adaptive behaviour in non humans which, when it is functioning as it was selected to do, creates a spandrel behaviour?<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In evolutionary biology, a spandrel is a phenotypic characteristic\n  that is a byproduct of the evolution of some other characteristic,\n  rather than a direct product of adaptive selection<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","question_id":31457,"tags":["evolution"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":61,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1429319534},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7701772ef9468d89e35dfc8d49f2fb92?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":9910,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9910/thaina","reputation":241,"display_name":"Thaina"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":42048,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452052880,"comment_id":71682,"body":"No. More importantly, if