d like confirmation from someone if I am understanding the definitions correctly.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Apomorphy<\/strong> -- any character state or trait novel to a species and its descendants. An apomorphy occurs when a taxon is selected to have a particular trait. <strong>Example:<\/strong> within the class reptilia, the suborder serpentes (snakes) has an apomorphy because its members have no legs. <\/li>\n<li><strong>Plesiomorphy<\/strong> -- an evolutionary trait or character state that is homologous within a particular taxon but is not unique to members of that group and therefore cannot be used as a diagnostic character for the group. <strong>Example:<\/strong> within the class reptilia, legs are a plesiomorphy for its members. <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>My Question:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Are these definitions and examples accurate? <\/p>\n","question_id":30617,"tags":["cladistics"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":30620,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2784,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1426900997},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1308aa2bd1c9c1d525138acc5b02cf09?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":9667,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9667/gugg","reputation":18,"display_name":"Gugg"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":26416,"edited":false,"creation_date":1420506632,"comment_id":42727,"body":"<a href=\"http://www.chem.uiowa.edu/arnold-research-group\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mark Arnold<\/a> and other&#39;s have done work on using near infrared spectrophotometry to measure blood glucose non-invasively, but I&#39;m not aware of any clinically approved methods available yet."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"http