otential height that you might predict based on genetics alone).<\/p>\n\n<p>When scientists are studying a gene in relation to a phenotype, they statistical methods to determine how much a genotype contributes to a phenotype. This process would minimize these types of fallacies since different alleles in different populations would be considered. However, sampling biases can occur and most human variation studies are done on people of european, asian, and african descent.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40360,"question_id":40335,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40335/have-there-been-any-chopstick-gene-mistakes-in-genetics","last_activity_date":1452047591,"creation_date":1446813415,"answer_count":1,"title":"Have there been any \"chopstick gene\" mistakes in genetics?","body":"<p>I've heard of the \"chopstick gene\" fallacy - wrongly assuming an association between genetics and some characteristic, confounded by non-genetic factors.<\/p>\n\n<p>Has this fallacy happened in real life?<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm not really interested in cases deliberately focusing on race, where people have argued that there's an innate difference between people of different races based on certain genetic differences, such as the putative \"warrior gene\" (\"warrior allele\"?) being described as more common in Maori people. As far as I can tell, the \"chopstick gene\" isn't about arguing that Asian people are better with chopsticks because of genetic differences between Asians and non-Asians.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm more interested in research that was done in good faith, which ignored the possibility of genetic variations having different frequencies in different groups, that produced erroneous conclusions.<\/p>\n","question_id":40335,"tags":["genetics","human-genetics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":false,"view_count":93,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/28af467eb309ca3d12cec68ace7b3f05?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20969,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20969/ruslan","reputation":106,"display_name":"Ruslan"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42046/what-are-some-examples-of-small-scale-physical-phenomena-that-snakes-fear","last_activity_date":1452042355,"creation_date":1452042355,"answer_count":0,"title":"What are some examples of small-scale physical phenomena that snakes fear?","body":"<p>What are some ways to use technology to repel snakes? <\/p>\n\n<p>One idea I was researching is low-frequency sound, which I read snakes could \"feel\" even though they are naturally deaf. Would this be a viable option? What sound ranges would need to be used?<\/p>\n\n<p>What are some other ways? Could targeted light be another option?<\/p>\n","question_id":42046,"tags":["zoology","ethology","snake"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":26,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/143b81297f570bf0e2f46ca724ebd305?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3538,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3538/user7924","reputation":48,"display_name":"user7924"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":0,"post_id":8282,"edited":false,"creation_date":1368128144,"comment_id":10492,"body":"This is similar to, but I think slightly different than <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/8026/what-is-the-function-of-nodes-of-ranvier-in-axons\" title=\"what is the function of nodes of ranvier in axons\">biology.stackexchange.com/questions/8026/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/143b81297f570bf0e2f46ca724ebd305?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"r