rong><\/p>\n\n<p>An indivdidual or a cell is said to be <em>homozygote<\/em> for a particular gene (or any DNA sequence) when identical <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allele\" rel=\"nofollow\">alleles<\/a> of the gene are present on both <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homologous_chromosome\" rel=\"nofollow\">homologous chromosomes<\/a>. (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zygosity\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia > Zygosity<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Homozygosis<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><em>Homozygosis<\/em> is the state of being <em>homozygote<\/em> (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1086014/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wright 1933<\/a>) for a particular gene (or any DNA sequence). According to <a href=\"http://www.thefreedictionary.com/homozygosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">freedictionary.com<\/a>, <em>homozygosis<\/em> may also refer to the process of formation of a <em>homozygote<\/em>. I have never encountered this sense in the literature though. As you found out by yourself, <em>Homozygosis<\/em> is a term that is rarely used in the literature (in comparison to <em>homozygote<\/em> and <em>homozygosity<\/em>)<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>Expected Homozygosity<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><em>Expected Homozygosity<\/em> is the probability of two randomly sampled alleles (in a population and at a given <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locus_(genetics)\" rel=\"nofollow\">locus<\/a>) to be <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_by_descent\" rel=\"nofollow\">identical by descent<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Expected homozygosity and Expected heterozygosity<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>As shown in <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/70/12/3321.short\" rel=\"nofollow\">Nei 1973<\/a>, the mathematical expression of expected homozygosity $Ho$ is<\/p>\n\n<p>$$Ho = \\sum_{a=1}^{n} x_a^2$$<\/p>\n\n<p>where $n$ is the number of alleles and $x_a$ is the frequency of the allele $a$.<\/p>\n\n<p>It is more common to use the concept of <em>expected heterozygosity<\/em> $He$ (a.k.a. gene diversity) rather than the one of <em>expected homozygosity<\/em> $Ho$. By definition, $He=1-Ho$, that is<\/p>\n\n<p>$$He =1- \\sum_{a=1}^{n} x_a^2$$<\/p>\n\n<p>In the special case of a bi-allelic locus, and replacing the two allele frequencies $x=1$ and $x=2$ by $p$ and $q=1-p$, the above formulations becomes<\/p>\n\n<p>$$Ho = p^2 + q^2$$\n$$He = 1 - (p^2 + q^2) = 2pq$$<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Under the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardy%E2%80%93Weinberg_principle#Deviations_from_Hardy.E2.80.93Weinberg_equilibrium\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hardy-Weinberg assumptions<\/a>, the observed frequency of heterozygote (a.k.a. observed heterozygosity) is equal to the expected heterozygosity and observed frequency of homozygotes (a.k.a. observed homozygosity) is equal to the expected homozygosity.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41938,"question_id":41934,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1452012872}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41934/is-there-is-difference-between-homozygosity-and-homozygosis","last_activity_date":1452013219,"creation_date":1451678599,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is there is difference between \"homozygosity\" and \"homozygosis\"?","body":"<p>Are these just two terms for the same phenomenon, i.e., the state of being homozygous? <a href=\"http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/homozygosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">Merriam-Webster<\/a> says so, but I know dictionaries sometimes miss the nuance of scientific terms. If they are indeed synonyms, it seems <em>homozygosity<\/em> has won out, according to <a href=\"https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=homozygosity%2Chomozygosis&amp;case_insensitive=on&amp;year_start=1900&amp;year_end=2000&amp;corpus=15&amp;smoothing=3&amp;share=&amp;direct_url=t4%3B%2Chomozygosity%3B%2Cc0%3B%2Cs0%3B%3Bhomozygosity%3B%2Cc0%3B%3BHomozygosity%3B%2Cc0%3B.t4%3B%2Chomozygosis%3B%2Cc0%3B%2Cs0%3B%3Bhomozygosis%3B%2Cc0%3B%3BHomozygosis%3B%2Cc0\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ngrams<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":41934,"tags":["genetics","terminology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":true,"view_count":40,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1452013219},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4dc62fdcf1289d6c904a3e781a0badc4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20865,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20865/j-ewqrth","reputation":6,"display_name":"J Ewqrth"},"closed_date":1452337891,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":2,"post_id":41853,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451393666,"comment_id":71263,"body":"I&#39;m voting to close this question as off-topic because it is better suited for Health SE, Fitness SE, or Hinduism SE."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"score":0,"post_id":41853,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1451394467,"comment_id":71264,"body":"@AMR please don&#39;t vote for migration because questions are &quot;better suited&quot; elsewhere. They should only be migrated if they are actually off-topic on the site they were posted at. Is it off-topic for Biology.SE? It&#39;s also likely not on-topic on Health.SE <a href=\"https://health.stackexchange.com/help/on-topic\">health.stackexchange.com/help/on-topic<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology