chinaants\" rel=\"nofollow\">AntWeb<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p>The colour is dark brown. The total length from the tip of the mandibles to the tip of the abdomen is about 17mm. The length of the large wing is also 17mm. I don't know what habitat it lives in and I also don't know how the workers or soldiers look like, as I have never seen where these ant queens emerge from.<\/p>\n\n<p>If anybody is fairly confident in identifying this species, I would also appreciate some tips about keeping it and starting a colony. I have a make-shift ant farm made out of two plastic bottles, one nested inside the other like a Russian doll. Out of the seven queens that I collected, three are already dying. A fourth one already show signs that she won't make it either.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>More info<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>When I picked them up, they were not exactly \"outdoors\". The short but heavy rain was mostly over and these queens were \"taking shelter\" in the stairwell of my building, which is usually dim, slightly damper and cooler than outside.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here are more pictures; these should be better because I just took these in natural daylight:\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/BAlWi.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/BAlWi.jpg\" alt=\"Head (ocelli)\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/XtFZd.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/XtFZd.jpg\" alt=\"Antenna\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/nH8wi.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/nH8wi.jpg\" alt=\"Mandibles\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/pYeZb.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/pYeZb.jpg\" alt=\"Head (side)\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Vje69.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Vje69.jpg\" alt=\"Whole (side)\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Somebody at <a href=\"http://antfarm.yuku.com/reply/148327/Ant-queen-identification-Hong-Kong-dark-brown-17mm-body-l#reply-148327\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Ant Farm and Myrmecology Forum<\/a> suggests that this is in the genus <em>Carebara<\/em> (previously <em>Pheidologeton<\/em>). After some more Google search of my own, and image comparing, I believe that this is indeed a <em>Carebara affinis<\/em>, which has previously been <a href=\"http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/861323\" rel=\"nofollow\">spotted in Hong Kong<\/a>. Could somebody confirm?<\/p>\n","question_id":38986,"tags":["species-identification","ant"],"score":20,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":261,"up_vote_count":20,"last_edit_date":1451733400},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0fc20bdaa2bbda327e40790844dafdd3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10204,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10204/cj-dennis","reputation":206,"display_name":"CJ Dennis"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c674c4a00c88fd4a89b1618b9d69f76?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20610,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20610/mmesser314","reputation":196,"display_name":"mmesser314"},"score":0,"post_id":42012,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451974426,"comment_id":71599,"body":"While it doesn&#39;t answer your specific question, a really good book for this kind of question is Your Inner Fish, by Neil Shubin."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42012/why-are-belly-buttons-on-the-stomach-why-does-the-umbilical-cord-end-up-attache","last_activity_date":1451954825,"creation_date":1451954825,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why are belly buttons on the stomach (why does the umbilical cord end up attached to the stomach)?","body":"<p>Belly buttons are at the site where the umbilical cord was attached to us as we developed inside our mothers. The same is true for all placental mammals.<\/p>\n\n<p>Why are belly buttons on the stomach? Why didn't the placement end up somewhere else like the chest, the back, the head, etc.? Is it optimal for the umbilical cord to be near the intestines?<\/p>\n","question_id":42012,"tags":["development","anatomy"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":31,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-fma8Illb9HM/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAALNQ/zC670-T_3II/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":20947,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20947/chandran-goodchild","reputation":1,"display_name":"Chandran Goodchild"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-fma8Illb9HM/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAALNQ/zC670-T_3II/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":20947,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20947/chandran-goodchild","reputation":1,"display_name":"Chandran Goodchild"},"score":0,"post_id":42010,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451946693,"comment_id":71590,"body":"I was just thinking, maybe turbidity could be used in combination with spectrophotometry as a way of measuring the cell population.   What about the dead cells though? They would also be detected right?  <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbidity\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbidity<\/a> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrophotometry\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrophotometry<\/a>"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42010/feasibility-of-smart-effective-microorganisms","last_activity_date":1451945343,"creation_date":1451945343,"answer_count":0,"title":"Feasibility of \"smart effective microorganisms\"","body":"<p>This might be a stupid question as I have little to no knowledge of biology, but I would really like to find out if it would be feasible to make such a system as a way of preventing infections.<\/p>\n\n<p>I recently read about \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effective_microorganism\" rel=\"nofollow\">Effective Microorganisms<\/a>\" (EM) as a way of covering surfaces with non-harmful bacteria in order to reduce the population growth of harmful bacteria. I really like this concept, but I also read that this treatment is usually a waste of money because the EM only survives in very specific conditions. <\/p>\n\n<p>What I would like to know is if it would be possible/feasible to make an advanced and evolving form of EM with a computer that systematically injects very small doses of specific bacteria into a sample and logs their effect on the sample. This data could then be collected in a large database and analysed to produce newer more promising versions of EM. Ideally if this were feasible, maybe it could even be implemented as a dynamic treatment in hospitals that continuously adapts and changes the ratio of the injected (good) bacteria depending on the current state of the patients infection.<\/p>\n\n<p>I suspect that the two main factors affecting the feasibility of this approach would be:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Time: How long (approximately/average) would the system have to wait after injecting a specific type bacteria into the sample, before the effects can be detected and a new type of bacteria can be injected?<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Detection: How can the bacterial population be measured (digitally) to produce such data without having to remove large amounts of the sample or destroy/contaminate the sample?<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>What other factors would have to be considered? What are the limitations?<\/p>\n\n<p>Again, I don't know much about biology so please forgive my uninformed questions...<\/p>\n","question_id":42010,"tags":["bacteriology","antibiotics","antibiotic-resistance"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":18,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b43f38490b21b6927f5d99dc5daefedd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17053,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17053/orphee","reputation":184,"display_name":"Orphee"},"closed_date":1452014006,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":42008,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451944573,"comment_id":71589,"body":"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chameleon#Change_of_color\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chameleon#Change_of_color<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef69e4c7ba6adf44fc3d17c4bbacec01?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10401,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10401/tanmath","reputation":1620,"display_name":"TanMath","accept_rate":58},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1451944151,"creation_date":1451944151,"body":"<p>When it comes to displaying color, most organisms use chromatophores. Chromatophores are pigment-containing and light-reflecting cells, or groups of cells. Chromatophores reflect the color that they look like.<\/p>\n\n<p>Chameleons also use chromatophores. The outermost layer of the chameleon\u2019s skin is transparent. Beneath this layer are the chromatophores. The deepest layer contains melanophores, which are filled with melanin. Above that layer are cells called iridophores, which have a blue pigment that reflects blue and white light. Layered on top of those cells are the xanthophores and erythrophores, which contain yellow and red pigments, respectively.<\/p>\n\n<p>For a chameleon to change color, it must expand or contract certain chromatophores depending on the signal of the nervous system. The expanded chromatophores block the contracted ones and the color of the expanded chromatophores determine the color of the chameleon. For example, to make the chameleon green, the iridophores and xanthophores must expand, and melanophores and and erythrophores contract.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>WIRED - <a href=\"http://www.wired.com/2014/04/how-do-chameleons-change-colors/\" rel=\"nofollow\">How Chameleons Change Colors<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>More to read<\/strong>\nThis Nature article provides a detail description and explanation of how this occurs - <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/ncomms/2015/150302/ncomms7368/full/ncomms7368.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Photonic crystals cause active colour change in chameleons<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":42009,"question_id":42008,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42008/how-chameleons-change-color","last_activity_date":1451944151,"creation_date":1451939768,"answer_count":1,"title":"How chameleons change color?","body":"<p>Well, I was watching a video about chameleons and I saw that their cells can change color. Can someone explain me how is this possible? <\/p>\n","question_id":42008,"tags":["cell-biology","zoology"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":42009,"down_vote_count":2,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":true,"view_count":35,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":41258,"edited":false,"creation_