r pupils have to shrink as much as possible in the sunlight, and, as you pointed out, vertical pupils can shrink more than circular ones. <\/p>\n\n<p>EDIT: People pointed out in the comments that cats have vertical eye pupils only in bright sunlight. In low-light conditions, the pupils expand to a circle. <\/p>\n","answer_id":7500,"question_id":7492,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1363193183},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550973bfc1f6c08ff29efee9a1cc7fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":2938,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2938/jack-aidley","reputation":3478,"display_name":"Jack Aidley"},"score":9,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1b1edcd1a52c43ea38daf015e81ee899?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3228,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3228/violet-giraffe","reputation":242,"display_name":"Violet Giraffe"},"score":0,"post_id":7514,"edited":false,"creation_date":1363180745,"comment_id":9389,"body":"I have thought about it, but don&#39;t understand how <i>exactly<\/i> non-circular hole negatively affects vision. For example: a heavily used Ñamera  lens can often have a broken iris, which takes irregular shape. The only clearly visible effect of this is the shape of unfocused background lights and other bright points. it doesn&#39;t worsen the sharp part of image in any immediately visible way. That&#39;s why I&#39;ve discarded this reason when thinking of pupils."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1363178421,"creation_date":1363178421,"body":"<p>Circular pupils are <em>always<\/em> functionally superior to vertical pupils; a slit does not correctly focus light from all directions whereas a circular pupil does. If you observe cats when they're hunting at dawn and dusk*, they have big, circular pupils; it's only when they're in bright light that the pupil shrinks to a slit. So why have vertical pupils at all? Because, as you mention they're capable of letting a more controlled range of light into the eye.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thus vertical slits let you be active in a wider range of light conditions at the cost of poorer vision in bright light; whilst circular pupils continue to function well in brighter light but at the cost of not allowing such a large range of control over the amount of light entering the eye.<\/p>\n\n<p>It is then easy to see why you get both kinds of pupil: circular pupils are favoured by animals that are typically active in bright light and need good vision under these circumstances; vertical pupils are favoured by animals that are primarily active in low light but need some ability to see in bright light.<\/p>\n\n<p>*- it's often stated that cats are nocturnal, this is untrue; cats are <em>crepuscular<\/em> - that is they are most active at dawn and dusk.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7514,"question_id":7492,"up_vote_count":9},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/5gsEz.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6758,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6758/smokeyvw","reputation":36,"display_name":"SmokeyVW"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":17485,"edited":false,"creation_date":1400367757,"comment_id":23891,"body":"How does a vertical pupil help to detect horizontal movement?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/5gsEz.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6758,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6758/smokeyvw","reputation":36,"display_name":"SmokeyVW"},"score":0,"post_id":17485,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=